Here is one example of how you can implement this (in Python):

def gcd(a,b):
    """
        Returns greatest common divisor of a and b.
    """
    a, b = min(a,b), max(a,b)
    if a==0:
        return b
    return gcd(b-a, a)
def gcd(a,b):
    """
        Returns greatest common divisor of a and b.
    """
    a, b = min(a,b), max(a,b)
    if a==0:
        return b
    return gcd(b-a, a)

The line a, b = min(a,b), max(a,b) just makes sure a is assigned the smallest number of the two arguments and b the largest.

First, consider the number of ways we can choose rrrr out of the nnnn people when order matters. This number is given by P(n,r) = \frac{n!}{(n-r)!}P(n,r)=n!(n−r)!P(n,r) = \frac{n!}{(n-r)!}P(n,r)=(n−r)!n!​. Now, this number is rrrr times larger than the number of circular rrrr-permutations of nnnn people. To see this, look at the following illustration

In the above figure, we have r=8r=8r=8r=8 distinct elements (people) and we want to consider all these rotations as one permutation. Therefore, we have to divide P(n,r)P(n,r)P(n,r)P(n,r) by rrrr to get the final answer.
